<header class="header">
  <h1>Crops That Need Fewer Than 1000 Growing Degree Days</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Extremely limited heat budgets require low thermal demand crops.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> defines the seasonal deadline for crop maturity.
    But in some climates, the greater limitation is total accumulated heat before frost returns.
    If your seasonal heat budget is under 1000 Growing Degree Days (GDD), crop selection must be precise.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Does “Under 1000 GDD” Mean?</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate uses 1991–2020 climate normals and frames frost timing at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your first frost date represents what typically happens — not an exact prediction.
  </p>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days measure accumulated heat, usually calculated with a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong> for warm-season crops.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    In very cool climates, especially at high elevations or northern latitudes,
    total seasonal accumulation may remain under 1000 GDD before frost risk returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your local seasonal heat budget using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Sub-1000 GDD Is Highly Constrained</h2>

  <p>
    Many warm-season crops require 1200–1800+ GDD to mature fully.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your climate accumulates fewer than 1000 GDD before first frost,
    those crops become extremely high-risk in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why heat-budget filtering is often more precise than counting frost-free days.
  </p>

  <p>
    For broader context on how frost and heat interact,
    see <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Crops That Typically Fit Under 1000 GDD</h2>

  <p>
    While exact requirements vary by variety and growing conditions,
    the following crops are generally compatible with very low heat budgets:
  </p>

  <h3>Leafy Greens</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Lettuce</li>
    <li>Spinach</li>
    <li>Arugula</li>
    <li>Mustard greens</li>
    <li>Kale</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These crops develop quickly and tolerate cool temperatures.
  </p>

  <h3>Quick Root Crops</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Radishes</li>
    <li>Turnips</li>
    <li>Baby beets</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Root crops often perform well because they do not rely on extended fruit ripening.
  </p>

  <h3>Cold-Tolerant Brassicas</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Baby cabbage varieties</li>
    <li>Fast-maturing broccoli types</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine">
    Exact GDD needs depend on cultivar, planting date, and local climate variation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Warm-Season Crops Under 1000 GDD?</h2>

  <p>
    In most cases, climates under 1000 GDD are not suitable for full-season warm crops like tomatoes, peppers, or winter squash.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ultra-early tomato varieties may approach viability in favorable microclimates,
    but margins are typically narrow.
  </p>

  <p>
    As discussed in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>,
    calendar-based maturity estimates often overstate feasibility in low-heat environments.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Evaluating Your Risk Margin</h2>

  <p>
    If your seasonal heat accumulation is near 1000 GDD,
    small variations in summer temperature can affect maturity outcomes.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because frost dates are probability-based,
    some years may accumulate slightly more or less heat than average.
  </p>

  <p>
    In borderline cases, focusing on:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Earlier-maturing varieties</li>
    <li>Transplanting at optimal frost-safe timing</li>
    <li>Using warm microclimates</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    may improve your margin.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can anchor transplant timing relative to frost boundaries using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Low-Heat Planning Model</h2>

  <p>
    In sub-1000 GDD climates, crop planning follows this framework:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost Boundary → Seasonal GDD → Crop Thermal Requirement → Risk Buffer</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    When your seasonal heat budget aligns with crop demand,
    maturity becomes realistic in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    When it does not, crop substitution is often more reliable than pushing margins.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Under 1000 GDD represents an extremely limited heat budget.</li>
    <li>Frost dates use a 32°F threshold and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Low heat-demand crops perform best in constrained climates.</li>
    <li>Warm-season crops carry high maturity risk under 1000 GDD.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In very low-heat climates, crop feasibility depends on aligning limited thermal accumulation
    with appropriate crop requirements.
  </p>
</section>